Here's a clean, production-ready Java solution for LeetCode 271 / LintCode 659. Encode and Decode Strings using the Length-Prefix Pattern:
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Codec {
    // Encodes a list of strings to a single string.
    public String encode(List<String> strs) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (String s : strs) {
            sb.append(s.length()).append('#').append(s);
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }

    // Decodes a single string to a list of strings.
    public List<String> decode(String s) {
        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int i = 0;
        while (i < s.length()) {
            // indexOf(int ch, int fromIndex): Finds the first occurrence of a character, 
            // starting the search forward from the specified index.
            int delimiter = s.indexOf('#', i);
            int len = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(i, delimiter));
            res.add(s.substring(delimiter + 1, delimiter + 1 + len));
            i = delimiter + 1 + len;
        }
        return res;
    }
}

Time Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of characters across all strings. Each character is written once during encode and read once during decode.
Space Complexity: O(N) for the encoded string and the decoded list. Auxiliary space is O(1).
🔍 Core Idea: Length-Prefix Encoding
Instead of relying on a delimiter that could appear inside the strings (like /, ,, or #), we prefix each string with its exact length followed by a separator. During decoding, the length tells us exactly how many characters to consume next, making the format completely unambiguous.
Example: ["abc", "a#b", ""] → "3#abc3#a#b0#"
- Read 3 → consume next 3 chars → "abc"
- Read 3 → consume next 3 chars → "a#b" (the # inside is safely consumed), because indexOf(int ch, int fromIndex): Finds the first occurrence of a character, starting the search forward from the specified index, e.g 3#a#bwill only retrieve first '#' and keep a#bintact 
- Read 0 → consume next 0 chars → ""
⏱️ Complexity
- Time: O(N) where N is the total number of characters across all strings. Each character is written once during encode and read once during decode.
- Space: O(N) for the encoded string and the decoded list. Auxiliary space is O(1).
💡 Why This Beats Naive Delimiter Approaches
ApproachProblemFixJust join with #"a#b"becomes ambiguousEscape delimiters (\#), but then you must also escape \ → cascading complexityFixed-width paddingWastes space, breaks if strings exceed paddingInefficient and constraint-dependentLength PrefixNoneDeterministic, O(1) overhead per string, handles any ASCII/Unicode content
🔧 Advanced Optimization (Manual Parsing)
If you want to avoid substring() and Integer.parseInt() overhead (useful in high-throughput systems), parse the length manually:
public List<String> decode(String s) {
    List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
    int i = 0;
    while (i < s.length()) {
        int len = 0;
        while (s.charAt(i) != '#') {
            len = len * 10 + (s.charAt(i) - '0');
            i++;
        }
        i++; // skip '#'
        res.add(s.substring(i, i + len));
        i += len;
    }
    return res;
}
Trade-off: Slightly faster in tight loops, but indexOf + parseInt is more readable and perfectly acceptable for interviews.
📝 Interview Checklist
- ✅ Always clarify: "Can strings contain any character?" → Yes, so length-prefix is mandatory.
- ✅ State why you chose # (or /) → Doesn't matter, length prefix makes it irrelevant.
- ✅ Mention empty list & empty string handling → Both work naturally with this approach.
- ✅ Note that StringBuilder avoids O(K * N) concatenation overhead where K is number of strings.
